# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: love2d
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:love2d/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:love2d/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Professional game development usually begins with a game design, which itself has several possible origins.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Occasionally the game development process starts with no clear design in mind, but as a series of experiments.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For example, game designer Will Wright began development of *The Sims* by getting programmers to experiment with several ideas.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Programmers are often required to produce prototypes of gameplay ideas and features.
[src:love2d/game-programming] A great deal of prototyping may take place during pre-production, before the design document is complete, and may help determine what features the design specifies.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Prototypes are developed quickly with very little time for up-front design and mostly act as a proof of concept or to test ideas.
[src:love2d/game-programming] They are not expected to work flawlessly, but are developed to try out new, sometimes exotic, ideas.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Though the programmer's main job is not to develop the game design, the programmers often contribute to the design, as do game artists.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The game designer will solicit input from both the producer and the art and programming lead for ideas and strategies for the game design.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Often individuals in non-lead positions also contribute, such as copywriters and other programmers and artists.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Programmers often closely follow the game design document.
[src:love2d/game-programming] As the game development progresses, the design document changes as programming limitations and new capabilities are discovered and exploited.
[src:love2d/game-programming] During production, programmers may create a great deal of source code to create the game described in the game's design document.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Along the way, the design document is modified to meet limitations or expanded to exploit new features.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The design document is very much a "living document", much of whose life is dictated by programmer's schedules, talent and resourcefulness.
[src:love2d/game-programming] While many programmers have some say in a game's content, most game producers solicit input from the lead programmer as to the status of a game programming development.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The lead is responsible for knowing the status of all facets of the game's programming and for pointing out limitations.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The lead programmer may also pass on suggestions from the programmers as to possible features they'd like to implement.
[src:love2d/game-programming] With today's visually rich content, the programmer must often interact with the art staff.
[src:love2d/game-programming] This very much depends on the programmer's role, of course.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For example, a 3D graphics programmer may need to work side by side with the game's 3D modelers discussing strategies and design considerations, while an AI programmer may need to interact very little, if at all, with the art staff.
[src:love2d/game-programming] To help artists and level designers with their tasks, programmers may volunteer or be called upon to develop tools and utilities.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Many of these may be for a specific purpose and can be buggy due to time constraints (time for development of such tools is often not included in a game's schedule) as well as because they are only for in-house use anyway.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Many game tools are developed in RAD languages for quicker development and may be discarded after the completion of the game.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The formal quality assurance testing process, performed by professional game testers, begins well into game development.
[src:love2d/game-programming] High-budget titles may begin testing with the first playable alpha, while low-budget and casual games might not enter testing until a release candidate is ready.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The programmers' task is to fix errors and bugs as such are discovered by the QA teams.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Final tasks include "polishing" the game, such as programmers fixing occasional bugs—from minor to catastrophic—that may arise during the last phases of testing.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Game developers may have a beta testing period, but the definition of such varies from developer to developer.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Often a beta contains all of the game's features, but may have a few bugs or incomplete content.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Few games are given a public beta period, for example, to measure stress tolerance for game servers.
[src:love2d/game-programming] When the game is deemed complete, it is said to have "gone gold" and is shipped off to the publisher.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Depending on circumstances, the publisher may then subject it to its own quality assurance or may begin pressing the game from the gold master.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Once a game ships, the maintenance phase for the video game begins.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Programmers wait for a period to get as many bug reports as possible.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Once the developer thinks they've obtained enough feedback, the programmers start working on a patch.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The patch may take weeks or months to develop, but it's intended to fix most bugs and problems with the game.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Occasionally a patch may include extra features or content or may even alter gameplay.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Most modern games take from one to three years to complete.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The length of development depends on a number of factors, but programming is required throughout all phases of development except the very early stages of game design.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Like other software, game development programs are generated from source code to the actual program (called the *executable*) by a compiler.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Source code can be developed with almost any text editor, but many professional game programmers use a full integrated development environment.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Once again, which IDE one uses depends on the target platform.
[src:love2d/game-programming] In addition to IDEs, many game development companies create custom tools developed to be used in-house.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some of these include prototypes and asset conversion tools (programs that change artwork, for example, into the game's custom format).
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some custom tools may even be delivered with the game, such as a level editor.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Game development companies are often very willing to spend thousands of dollars to make sure their programmers are well equipped with the best tools.
[src:love2d/game-programming] A well outfitted programmer may have two to three development systems and multiple monitors dominating their office or cubicle.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Once the game's initial design has been agreed upon, the development language must be decided upon.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The choice depends upon many factors, such as language familiarity of the programming staff, target platforms, the execution speed requirements and the language of any game engines, APIs or libraries being used.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For personal computers, the language selected may be little more than a matter of preference.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Language bindings for popular libraries such as SDL and Allegro are widespread, and the performance gap between idiomatic code written in modern compiled languages is negligible.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The most popular languages are usually procedural or object-oriented and implemented via compilers; for example, C, C++, and Java.
[src:love2d/game-programming] However, developers may take into account domain-specific features, such as interfacing with the operating system, and resilience to reverse engineering for online video games.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Many games are not written in one language exclusively, and may combine two or more languages; For example, Unity, a popular game engine, has different pieces written in C, C++, and C#.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For consoles, the support of the target platform is usually the most considered factor.
[src:love2d/game-programming] In the past, video games for consoles were written almost exclusively in assembly due to limited resources in terms of both storage and processing speed.
[src:love2d/game-programming] However, as technology has advanced, so have the options for game development on consoles.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Nintendo, Microsoft, and Sony all have differing SDKs for their Nintendo Switch, Xbox One, and PlayStation 4 consoles, respectively.
[src:love2d/game-programming] High-level scripting languages are increasingly being used as embedded extensions to the underlying game written in a compiled programming language, for the convenience of both the original developer and anyone who would wish to mod the game.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Lua is a very popular choice, as its API is written in ANSI C and the language is designed to be embedded into other applications.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Many developers have created custom languages altogether for their games, such as id Software's QuakeC and Epic Games' UnrealScript.
[src:love2d/game-programming] A key decision in game programming is which, if any, APIs and libraries to use.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Today, there are numerous libraries available which take care of key tasks of game programming.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some libraries can handle sound processing, input, and graphics rendering.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some can even handle some AI tasks such as pathfinding.
[src:love2d/game-programming] There are even entire game engines that handle most of the tasks of game programming and only require coding game logic.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Which APIs and libraries one chooses depends largely on the target platform.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For example, libraries for PlayStation 2 development may not be available for Microsoft Windows and vice versa.
[src:love2d/game-programming] However, there are game frameworks available that allow or ease cross-platform development, so programmers can program a game in a single language and have the game run on several platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, PSP and Microsoft Windows.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Today, graphics are a key defining feature of most games.
[src:love2d/game-programming] While 2D graphics used to be the norm for games released through the mid-1990s, most AAA games now boast full 3D graphics, even for games which are largely 2D in nature, such as *Civilization III*.
[src:love2d/game-programming] However, purely 2D graphics have experienced a Renaissance with indie games.
[src:love2d/game-programming] A well established personal computer platform is Microsoft Windows.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Since it came pre-installed on almost ninety percent of PCs sold, it now has the largest user base.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The two most popular 3D graphics APIs for Microsoft Windows are Direct3D and OpenGL.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The benefits and weaknesses of each API are hotly debated among Windows game programmers.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Currently, the most popular Computing platform is Google Android.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Since it comes pre-installed on almost eighty percent of Smartphones sold, Android has the second largest user base, and increasing.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Direct3D is freely available from Microsoft, as are the rest of the DirectX APIs.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Microsoft developed DirectX for game programmers and continues to add features to the API.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The DirectX specification is not controlled by an open arbitration committee and Microsoft is free to add, remove or change features.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Direct3D is not portable; it is designed specifically for Microsoft Windows and no other platform (though a form of Direct3D is used on Microsoft's Xbox, Windows Phone 7.5 smartphones and mobile devices which run the Pocket PC operating system).
[src:love2d/game-programming] Code written with OpenGL is easily ported between platforms with a compatible implementation.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For example, *Quake II*, which uses OpenGL, was ported from Windows to Linux by a fan of the game.
[src:love2d/game-programming] OpenGL is a standard maintained by the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (ARB).
[src:love2d/game-programming] The ARB meets periodically to update the standard by adding emerging support for features of the latest 3D hardware.
[src:love2d/game-programming] In addition, the development tools provided by the manufacturers of some video game consoles (such as the Nintendo GameCube, the Nintendo DS, and the PSP) use graphic APIs that resemble OpenGL.
[src:love2d/game-programming] OpenGL often lags behind on feature updates due to the lack of a permanent development team and the requirement that implementations begin development after the standard has been published.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Programmers who choose to use it can access some hardware's latest 3D features, but only through non-standardized extensions.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The situation may change in the future as the OpenGL architecture review board (ARB) has passed control of the specification to the Khronos Group in an attempt to counter the problem.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For development on Microsoft Windows, the various APIs of DirectX may be used for input, sound effects, music, networking and the playback of videos.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Many commercial libraries are available to accomplish these tasks, but since DirectX is available for free, it is the most widely used.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For console programming, the console manufacturers provide facilities for rendering graphics and the other tasks of game development.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The console manufacturers also provide complete development systems, without which one cannot legally market nor develop games for their system.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Third-party developers also sell toolkits or libraries that ease the development on one or more of these tasks or provide special benefits, such as cross-platform development capabilities.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The central component of any game, from a programming standpoint, is the *game loop*.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The game loop allows the game to run smoothly regardless of a user's input or lack thereof.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Most traditional software programs respond to user input and do nothing without it.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For example, a word processor formats words and text as a user types.
[src:love2d/game-programming] If the user doesn't type anything, the word processor does nothing.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some functions may take a long time to complete, but all are initiated by a user telling the program to do something.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Games, on the other hand, must continue to operate *regardless* of a user's input.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The loop may be refined and modified as game development progresses, but most games are based on this basic idea.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Game loops differ depending on the platform they are developed for.
[src:love2d/game-programming] For example, games written for DOS and many consoles can dominate and exploit available processing resources without restraint.
[src:love2d/game-programming] However, games for a modern PC operating system such as Microsoft Windows must operate within the constraints of the process scheduler.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some modern games run multiple threads so that, for example, the computation of character AI can be decoupled from the generation of smooth motion within the game.
[src:love2d/game-programming] This has the disadvantage of (slightly) increased overhead, but the game may run more smoothly and efficiently on hyper-threading or multicore processors and on multiprocessor platforms.
[src:love2d/game-programming] With the computer industry's focus on CPUs with more cores that can execute more threads, this is becoming increasingly important.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Consoles like the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 already have more than one core per processor, and execute more than one thread per core.
[src:love2d/game-programming] The only platforms widely available for hobbyists to program are consumer operating systems, such as Android, iOS, Windows, Mac, Linux, etc.
[src:love2d/game-programming] This is because development on game consoles requires special development systems that cost thousands of dollars.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Often these must be obtained from the console manufacturer and are only sold or leased to professional game development studios.
[src:love2d/game-programming] However, Microsoft used to distribute a game development framework, XNA, which runs on both Microsoft Windows and Xbox 360.
[src:love2d/game-programming] XNA was discontinued, but other projects like MonoGame and SharpDX are trying to allow the same access for game coding.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some hobbyists also develop homebrew games, especially for handheld systems or modded consoles.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some software engineering students program games as exercises for learning a programming language or operating system.
[src:love2d/game-programming] Some hobbyists may use software packages that help with game development, such as Adobe Animate, Unity, Android Studio, pygame, Adventure Game Studio, Roblox Studio, GameMaker Studio, Godot, Unreal Engine, Pixel Game Maker MV, or Construct.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua originated in 1993 as a language for extending software applications to meet the increasing demand for customization at the time.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] It provided the basic facilities of most procedural programming languages, but more complicated or domain-specific features were not included; rather, it included mechanisms for extending the language, allowing programmers to implement such features.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] As Lua was intended to be a general embeddable extension language, the designers of Lua focused on improving its speed, portability, extensibility and ease-of-use in development.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua was created in 1993 by Roberto Ierusalimschy, Luiz Henrique de Figueiredo, and Waldemar Celes, members of the Computer Graphics Technology Group (Tecgraf) at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro, in Brazil.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] From 1977 until 1992, Brazil had a policy of strong trade barriers (called a market reserve) for computer hardware and software, believing that Brazil could and should produce its own hardware and software.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] In that climate, Tecgraf's clients could not afford, either politically or financially, to buy customized software from abroad; under the market reserve, clients would have to go through a complex bureaucratic process to prove their needs couldn't be met by Brazilian companies.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Those reasons led Tecgraf to implement the basic tools it needed from scratch.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua's predecessors were the data-description and configuration languages Simple Object Language (SOL) and Data-Entry Language (DEL).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] They had been independently developed at Tecgraf in 1992–1993 to add some flexibility into two different projects (both were interactive graphical programs for engineering applications at Petrobras company).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] There was a lack of any flow-control structures in SOL and DEL, and Petrobras felt a growing need to add full programming power to them.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua 1.0 was designed in such a way that its object constructors, being then slightly different from the current light and flexible style, incorporated the data-description syntax of SOL (hence the name Lua: *Sol* meaning "Sun" in Portuguese, and *Lua* meaning "Moon").
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Dobb's Journal*, Lua's creators also state that LISP and Scheme with their single, ubiquitous data-structure mechanism (the list) were a major influence on their decision to develop the table as the primary data structure of Lua.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua semantics have been increasingly influenced by Scheme over time, especially with the introduction of anonymous functions and full lexical scoping.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Several features were added in new Lua versions.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Versions of Lua prior to version 5.0 were released under a license similar to the BSD license.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] From version 5.0 onwards, Lua has been licensed under the MIT License.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Both are permissive free software licences and are almost identical.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua is commonly described as a "multi-paradigm" language, providing a small set of general features that can be extended to fit different problem types.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua does not contain explicit support for inheritance, but allows it to be implemented with metatables.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] In general, Lua strives to provide simple, flexible meta-features that can be extended as needed, rather than supply a feature-set specific to one programming paradigm.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] As a result, the base language is light; the full reference interpreter is only about 293 kB compiled and easily adaptable to a broad range of applications.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] As a dynamically typed language intended for use as an extension language or scripting language, Lua is compact enough to fit on a variety of host platforms.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] It supports only a small number of atomic data structures such as Boolean values, numbers (double-precision floating point and 64-bit integers by default) and strings.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Typical data structures such as arrays, sets, lists and records can be represented using Lua's single native data structure, the table, which is essentially a heterogeneous associative array.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua implements a small set of advanced features such as first-class functions, garbage collection, closures, proper tail calls, coercion (automatic conversion between string and number values at run time), coroutines (cooperative multitasking) and dynamic module loading.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The declaration of a variable, without a value.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A comment in Lua starts with a double-hyphen and runs to the end of the line, similar to Ada, Eiffel, Haskell, SQL and VHDL.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Multi-line strings and comments are marked with double square brackets.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua has one type of conditional test: `if then end` with optional `else` and `elseif then` execution control constructs.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua has four types of conditional loops: the `while` loop, the `repeat` loop (similar to a `do while` loop), the numeric `for` loop and the generic `for` loop.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Loops can also be nested (put inside of another loop).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Any future calls to `print` will now be routed through the new function, and because of Lua's lexical scoping, the old print function will only be accessible by the new, modified print.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A new closure for the variable `x` is created every time `addto` is called, so that each new anonymous function returned will always access its own `x` parameter.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The closure is managed by Lua's garbage collector, just like any other object.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Tables are the most important data structures (and, by design, the only built-in composite data type) in Lua and are the foundation of all user-created types.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] They are associative arrays with addition of automatic numeric key and special syntax.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A table is a set of key and data pairs, where the data is referenced by key; in other words, it is a hashed heterogeneous associative array.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Tables are created using the `{}` constructor syntax.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Tables are always passed by reference (see Call by sharing).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A key (index) can be any value except `nil` and NaN, including functions.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A table is often used as structure (or record) by using strings as keys.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Because such use is very common, Lua features a special syntax for accessing such fields.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] By using a table to store related functions, it can act as a namespace.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Tables are automatically assigned a numerical key, enabling them to be used as an array data type.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The first automatic index is 1 rather than 0 as it is for many other programming languages (though an explicit index of 0 is allowed).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A numeric key `1` is distinct from a string key `"1"`.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The length of a table `t` is defined to be any integer index `n` such that `t[n]` is not `nil` and `t[n+1]` is `nil`; moreover, if `t[1]` is `nil`, `n` can be zero.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] For a regular array, with non-nil values from 1 to a given `n`, its length is exactly that `n`, the index of its last value.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] If the array has "holes" (that is, nil values between other non-nil values), then `#t` can be any of the indices that directly precedes a `nil` value (that is, it may consider any such nil value as the end of the array).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Using a hash map to emulate an array is normally slower than using an actual array; however, Lua tables are optimized for use as arrays to help avoid this issue.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Extensible semantics is a key feature of Lua, and the metatable allows powerful customization of tables.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The following example demonstrates an "infinite" table.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] For any `n`, `fibs[n]` will give the `n`-th Fibonacci number using dynamic programming and memoization.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Although Lua does not have a built-in concept of classes, object-oriented programming can be emulated using functions and tables.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] An object is formed by putting methods and fields in a table.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Inheritance (both single and multiple) can be implemented with metatables, delegating nonexistent methods and fields to a parent object.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] There is no such concept as "class" with these techniques; rather, prototypes are used, similar to Self or JavaScript.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] New objects are created either with a factory method (that constructs new objects from scratch) or by cloning an existing object.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Here, `setmetatable` tells Lua to look for an element in the `Vector` table if it is not present in the `vec` table.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] `vec.magnitude`, which is equivalent to `vec["magnitude"]`, first looks in the `vec` table for the `magnitude` element.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The `vec` table does not have a `magnitude` element, but its metatable delegates to the `Vector` table for the `magnitude` element when it's not found in the `vec` table.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua provides some syntactic sugar to facilitate object orientation.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] To declare member functions inside a prototype table, one can use `function table:func(args)`, which is equivalent to `function table.func(self, args)`.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Calling class methods also makes use of the colon: `object:func(args)` is equivalent to `object.func(object, args)`.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] It is possible to use metatables to mimic the behavior of class inheritance in Lua.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] In this example, we allow vectors to have their values multiplied by a constant in a derived class.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] It is also possible to implement multiple inheritance; `__index` can either be a function or a table.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Operator overloading can also be done; Lua metatables can have elements such as `__add`, `__sub` and so on.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua programs are not interpreted directly from the textual Lua file, but are compiled into bytecode, which is then run on the Lua virtual machine (VM).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The compiling process is typically invisible to the user and is performed during run-time, especially when a just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler is used, but it can be done offline to increase loading performance or reduce the memory footprint of the host environment by leaving out the compiler.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua bytecode can also be produced and executed from within Lua, using the `dump` function from the string library and the `load/loadstring/loadfile` functions.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua version 5.5.0 is implemented in approximately 32,000 lines of C code.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Like most CPUs, and unlike most virtual machines (which are stack-based), the Lua VM is register-based, and therefore more closely resembles most hardware design.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The register architecture both avoids excessive copying of values, and reduces the total number of instructions per function.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The virtual machine of Lua 5 is one of the first register-based pure VMs to have a wide use.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Parrot and Android's Dalvik are two other well-known register-based VMs.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua is intended to be embedded into other applications, and provides a C API for this purpose.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The API is divided into two parts: the Lua core and the Lua auxiliary library.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The Lua API's design eliminates the need for manual reference counting (management) in C code, unlike Python's API.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The API, like the language, is minimalist.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Advanced functions are provided by the auxiliary library, which consists largely of preprocessor macros which assist with complex table operations.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua provides functions to push and pop most simple C data types (integers, floats, etc.) to and from the stack, and functions to manipulate tables through the stack.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The Lua stack is somewhat different from a traditional stack; the stack can be indexed directly, for example.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Negative indices indicate offsets from the top of the stack.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] For example, −1 is the top (most recently pushed value), while positive indices indicate offsets from the bottom (oldest value).
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Marshalling data between C and Lua functions is also done using the stack.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] To call a Lua function, arguments are pushed onto the stack, and then the `lua_call` is used to call the actual function.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] When writing a C function to be directly called from Lua, the arguments are read from the stack.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] The C API also provides some special tables, located at various "pseudo-indices" in the Lua stack.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] At `LUA_GLOBALSINDEX` prior to Lua 5.2 is the globals table, `_G` from within Lua, which is the main namespace.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] There is also a registry located at `LUA_REGISTRYINDEX` where C programs can store Lua values for later retrieval.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Besides standard library (core) modules it is possible to write extensions using the Lua API.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Extension modules are shared objects which can be used to extend the functions of the interpreter by providing native facilities to Lua scripts.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Lua scripts may load extension modules using `require`, just like modules written in Lua itself, or with `package.loadlib`.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] When a C library is loaded via `require('foo')` Lua will look for the function `luaopen_foo` and call it, which acts as any C function callable from Lua and generally returns a table filled with methods.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] A growing set of modules termed *rocks* are available through a package management system named LuaRocks, in the spirit of CPAN, RubyGems and Python eggs.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Prewritten Lua bindings exist for most popular programming languages, including other scripting languages.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] For C++, there are a number of template-based approaches and some automatic binding generators.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] In video game development, Lua is widely used as a scripting language, mainly due to its perceived ease of embedding, fast execution, and short learning curve.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Notable games which use Lua include *Roblox*, *Garry's Mod*, *World of Warcraft*, *Payday 2*, *Project Zomboid*, *Phantasy Star Online 2*, *Dota 2*, *Crysis*, and many others.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] Also, Lua is used in non-video game software, such as Adobe Lightroom, Moho, iClone, Aerospike, and some system software in FreeBSD and NetBSD, and used as a template scripting language on MediaWiki using the Scribunto extension.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] In 2003, a poll conducted by GameDev.net showed that Lua was the most popular scripting language for game programming.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] On 12 January 2012, Lua was announced as a winner of the Front Line Award 2011 from the magazine *Game Developer* in the category Programming Tools.
[src:love2d/lua-programming-language] In addition, the Lua users community provides some *power patches* on top of the reference C implementation.
[src:love2d/luajit] The LuaJIT project was started in 2005 by developer Mike Pall, released under the MIT open source license.
[src:love2d/luajit] The second major release of the compiler, 2.0.0, featured major performance increases.
[src:love2d/luajit] Mike Pall, the creator and maintainer recommends using the tip of the v2.1 branch, and does not believe in releases.
[src:love2d/luajit] Mike Pall resigned in 2015 making only occasional patching to the future 2.1 version since then.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT is often the fastest Lua runtime.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT has also been named the fastest implementation of a dynamic programming language.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT includes a Foreign Function Interface compatible with C data structures.
[src:love2d/luajit] Its use is encouraged for numerical computation.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT is a tracing just-in-time compiler.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT chooses loops and function calls as trace anchors to begin recording possible hot paths.
[src:love2d/luajit] Function calls will require twice as many invocations to begin recording as a loop.
[src:love2d/luajit] Once LuaJIT begins recording, all control flow, including jumps and calls, are inlined to form a linear trace.
[src:love2d/luajit] All executed bytecode instructions are stored and incrementally converted into LuaJIT's static single-assignment intermediate representation.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT's trace compiler is often capable of inlining and removing dispatches from object orientation, operators, and type modifications.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT uses two types of internal representation.
[src:love2d/luajit] A stack-based bytecode is used for the interpreter, and a static single-assignment form is used for the just-in-time compiler.
[src:love2d/luajit] The interpreter bytecode is frequently patched by the JIT compiler, often to begin executing a compiled trace or to mark a segment of bytecode for causing too many trace aborts.
[src:love2d/luajit] LuaJIT adds several extensions to its base implementation, Lua 5.1, most of which do not break compatibility.
[src:love2d/löve-game-framework] The API provided by the framework gives access to the video and sound functions of the host machine through the libraries SDL and OpenGL, or since version 0.10 also OpenGL ES 2 and 3.
[src:love2d/löve-game-framework] Fonts can be rendered by the FreeType engine.
[src:love2d/löve-game-framework] A version of the framework called piLöve has been specifically ported to Raspberry Pi.
[src:love2d/löve-game-framework] The framework is frequently found in the compositions of video game development competitions, such as the game development competition Ludum Dare.
[src:love2d/löve-game-framework] In July 2018, it was the 10th most popular game development software used by independent game developers on the site Itch.io, holding a 1.97% share.
[src:love2d/löve-game-framework] There are various libraries and forks of LÖVE to improve basic functions, such as OOP with inheritance and overloading, interpolations, cameras, gamestates, etc.
